[2
Date: 29 Jun 2000
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Reuters, 29 Jun 2000 [edited

UK finds BSE cow born after August 1996
-----------------------------------------
Britain announced a cow born after measures were introduced to eradicate
mad cow disease (Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy, BSE) had been found to
have BSE.
"An animal born on August 25, 1996 was confirmed as a BSE case on June 27
this year," Agriculture Minister Nick Brown told parliament.
"The date is significant because it is after August 1, 1996, when extra
control measures on animal feed, containing mammalian meat and bone
meal...had been implemented."
"Experts have always foreseen a few cases of BSE could be confirmed in
animals born after August 1, 1996," he said. "There is no risk to food
safety as a result of this case."
A European Union-wide export ban on British beef was imposed in March 1996
at the height of the crisis over BSE after Britain admitted there was a
link with a new variant form of Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (nvCJD) has so
far killed more than 50 people.
Brown said there had been no chance of the cow being exported as beef under
the Date-Based Export Scheme because it was too old and its mother had been
slaughtered in November 1996, less than 3 months after the animal concerned
was born. The scheme allows only deboned beef from animals aged between 6
and 30 months to be sold abroad.
An assessment last year on behalf of SEAC (the Spongiform Encephalopathy
Advisory Committee) assumed by the end of 2000, up to 19 cases born after
August 1996 might be identified, Brown said. "This is the first and only
case so far."
